 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:2000s in Tokyo]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2007_Komae_city_assembly_election"}
{"title_page": "My Sister, My Sitter", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox Simpsons episode\n| title      = Me Sister, Me Sitter\n| image      = \n| caption    = \n| season     = 8\n| episode    = 17\n| director   = [[Jim Reardon]]<ref name=\"bbc\"/>\n| writer     = [[Dan Greaney]]<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/simpsons/episodeguide/season8/page17.shtml|title=My Sister, My Sitter|access-date=May 2, 2007|last1=Martyn|first1=Warren|last2=Wood|first2=Adrian|year=2000|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n| production = 4F13\n| airdate    = {{start date|1997|03|02}}<ref name=\"officialsite\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thesimpsons.com/#/recaps/season-8_episode-17|title=My Sister, My Sitter|access-date=May 2, 2007|publisher=The Simpsons.com}}</ref>\n| couch_gag  = The living room is on a ship being tossed by a stormy ocean. The Simpsons, decked out in raingear, run to the couch, but get washed away by a large wave.<ref name=\"bbc\"/>\n| commentary = [[Matt Groening]]<br>[[Josh Weinstein]]<br>Molly Weinstein<br>Simon Weinstein<br>[[Yeardley Smith]]<br>[[Jim Reardon]]<br>[[George Meyer]]\n| prev       = [[Brother from Another Series]]\n| next       = [[Homer vs. the Eighteenth Amendment]]\n}}\n\"'''My Sister, My Sitter'''\" is the seventeenth episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki> [[The Simpsons (season 8)|eighth season]]. It originally aired on the [[Fox network]] in the United States on March 2, 1997. In the episode, Marge and Homer leave Lisa to babysit Bart and Maggie. Annoyed that his younger sister is his babysitter, Bart does everything he can to annoy her. When Bart is injured, Lisa must find him medical attention without spoiling her reputation as a good babysitter.\n\nThe episode was written by [[Dan Greaney]] and directed by [[Jim Reardon]]. The script was written to focus on the relationship between Bart and Lisa and the episode has further been used{{by whom?|date=March 2020}} to discuss the difficulties in letting children babysit themselves. The episode received mostly positive reviews.\n\n==Plot==\nInspired by ''[[The Baby-Sitters Club]]'' series of novels, [[Lisa Simpson|Lisa]] decides to become a babysitter, but no one takes her seriously because of her age. When [[Maude Flanders|Maude]] is taken hostage in Lebanon, [[Ned Flanders|Ned]] must leave suddenly to get her released. In his haste, he agrees to let Lisa babysit [[Rod and Todd Flanders|Rod and Todd]]. Ned puts out the good word for Lisa, who experiences a business boom.\n\nInspired by the success of [[Baltimore]]'s [[Inner Harbor|revamped wharf]], the [[Springfield (The Simpsons)|Springfield]] Squidport reopens and throws a gala. [[Homer Simpson|Homer]] and [[Marge Simpson|Marge]] attend, leaving Lisa to babysit [[Bart Simpson|Bart]] and [[Maggie Simpson|Maggie]]. Bart is upset that his younger sister is his babysitter; Lisa thinks his childish antics warrant it. Bart torments Lisa by having a giant [[submarine sandwich]] delivered, hiring [[Krusty the Clown|Krusty]] for a bachelor party, claiming that Lisa saw a [[UFO]], dialing {{nobr|9-1-1}} for a \"sisterectomy\", and feeding Maggie coffee ice cream for dinner.\n\nBart's pranks anger Lisa so much that she lunges at him, causing him to fall down the stairs, dislocating his shoulder and causing a large bump on his head. Bart realizes if Lisa fails to take him to a nearby hospital, her reputation as a babysitter will be ruined. To make his condition worse, Bart locks himself in his room and repeatedly hits his head on the door, eventually knocking himself unconscious. \n\nLisa tries to call for an ambulance, but the {{nobr|9-1-1}} operator refuses to assist her due to Bart's earlier prank calls. Lisa considers asking [[Dr. Hibbert]] for help, but realizes that would ruin her reputation as a babysitter. Instead she takes Bart to [[Dr. Nick Riviera]]'s clinic in a wheelbarrow, bringing Maggie along in a [[pet carrier]] because the coffee ice cream has overstimulated her. Lisa is unable to see the doctor due to a long queue in the waiting room.\n\nFrantic, Lisa tries to wheel Bart and Maggie to the hospital. She loses control of the wheelbarrow and it rolls down a cliff into a muddy river &mdash; in front of aghast onlookers at the Squidport. The crowd assumes Lisa is on drugs, has murdered Bart, and is about to drown the caged Maggie. Lisa reveals none of the crowd's suspicions are true, but her reputation is ruined.\n\nLater Bart, whose injuries have been treated, apologizes to Lisa for causing the ordeal and ruining her babysitting business. She forgives him, but feels bad for being called the \"World's Worst Babysitter\". Much to her delight, she receives babysitting requests from Dr. Hibbert and Ned Flanders because they cannot find any other sitters.\n\n==Production and themes==\n[[File:USS-Constellation-Szmurlo.jpg|thumb|The Squidport was inspired by waterfront renovations such as [[Harborplace]] in [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]].]]\nThe episode was directed by [[Jim Reardon]] and written by [[Dan Greaney]].<ref name=\"bbc\"/> Like numerous preceding episodes, \"My Sister, My Sitter\" deals with the relationship between Bart and Lisa. Greaney specializes in writing Bart and Lisa episodes from the perspective of a kid.<ref name=\"Weinstein\">{{cite AV media|last=Weinstein|first=Josh|date=2006|title=Commentary for \"My Sister, My Sitter\". The Simpsons: The Complete Eighth Season|medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> Elaine E Sutherland, who is a member of the Law Society of Scotland's Family Law Sub-Committee and Professor of Child and Family Law at the Law School, Stirling University, used the episode to describe the potential problems of letting one of your kids babysit the rest. While one child may be mature enough to babysit, it is not certain that the other kids accept the babysitter's authority.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edinburghnews.scotsman.com/opinion/Elaine-Sutherland-A-parents-guide.6816766.jp|title=Elaine Sutherland: A parent's guide to choosing who looks after baby|last=Sutherland|first=Elaine|work=Edinburgh Evening News|date=August 11, 2011|access-date=September 5, 2011}}</ref> According to Alan S. Brown and Chris Logan, the writers of the book ''[[The Psychology of The Simpsons|The Psychology of the Simpsons: D\u2019oh!]]'', the episode is an example of how feminine anger rarely solves the problem on ''The Simpsons''. \u201cHere, Lisa\u2019s rage and ongoing frustration contribute to her difficulty in making good decisions about what to do with her emotion,\u201d they write.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Brown|first1=Alan|last2=Logan|first2=Chris|year=2006|title=The Psychology of The Simpsons|title-link=The Psychology of The Simpsons|pages=114\u2013115|isbn=1-932100-70-9}}</ref> Keeping with the babysitter theme, there are cultural references to ''[[The Baby-Sitters Club]]'': Lisa reads book #14 - The Formula Formula, while Janey is on book #20 - The President's Baby Is Missing.<ref name=\"bbc\"/>\n\nThe idea of revamping the waterfront came from cities like [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]], who were always trying to fix formerly horrible places.<ref name=\"Weinstein\"/> [[Chris Turner (author)|Chris Turner]], the author of the book ''[[Planet Simpson]]'', writes about the scene at the Squidport: \"The \"satirical\" setting seems almost documentary\". The Squidport is a local revitalization project, which recast a historic industrial area as a pedestrian mall. He calls this an example of how \u201chyper-consumer culture of Springfield moves front and center\u201d{{sfn|Turner|2004|p=106}} On the waterfront, Rainier Wolfcastle opens a restaurant called \"Planet Hype\".{{sfn|Turner|2004|p=106}} This is a parody of the international theme restaurant franchise [[Planet Hollywood]].<ref name=\"Weinstein\" /> Wolfcastle is a parody of [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]],{{sfn|Turner|2004|p=385}} who launched Planet Hollywood along with Sylvester Stallone, Bruce Willis, Demi Moore and Whoopi Goldberg in 1991.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/id/2086889/|title=Arnold's Bad Business|author=Gross, Daniel|work=Slate|date=August 11, 2003|access-date=September 5, 2011}}</ref> According to [[Matt Groening]], the show had written an entire episode around Planet Hollywood, which featured the voices of Schwarzenegger, Stallone, and Willis as [[The Three Stooges]] type of characters. The episode was never animated, because it turned out that it was only the publicist of Planet Hollywood's idea and the actors did not want to participate.<ref>{{cite AV media|last=Groening|first=Matt|date=2006|title=Commentary for \"My Sister, My Sitter\". The Simpsons: The Complete Eighth Season|medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nIn its original broadcast, \"My Sister, My Sitter\" finished 47th in ratings in a tie with ''[[Melrose Place]]'' for the week of February 24 \u2013 March 2, 1997, with a [[Nielsen ratings|Nielsen rating]] of 9.0, equivalent to approximately 8.7 million viewing households. It was the fifth highest-rated show on the Fox network that week.<ref>{{cite news|title=Prime-time ratings|work=The Orange County Register|page=F02|date=March 5, 1997}}</ref> \n\nSince airing, the episode has received mostly positive reviews from television critics. The authors of the book ''I Can't Believe It's a Bigger and Better Updated Unofficial Simpsons Guide'', Warren Martyn and Adrian Wood, called it \"a clever episode, if a little disjointed&nbsp;\u2014 the two stories don't gel as well as normal.\"<ref name=\"bbc\"/> \n\nTim Raynor of DVDTown.com said that the episode \"is full of the usual, fun antics that you would expect from Bart or any of the other dumb Simpsons.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdtown.com/reviews/dvd-simpsons-the-the-complete-8th-season/3886|title=Simpsons, The: The Complete 8th Season (DVD)|last=Raynor|first=Tim|date=August 21, 2006|publisher=DVDTown.com|access-date=April 23, 2009|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928084257/http://www.dvdtown.com/reviews/dvd-simpsons-the-the-complete-8th-season/3886|archive-date=September 28, 2011}}</ref> \n\nDVD Movie Guide's Colin Jacobson said that \"the segments in which Lisa babysits the various kids in town are a delight\" and that the episode \"mixes wacky moments with reality as it places Lisa in a logical position. Her conflict with Bart creates realism and also brings out the comedy.\"<ref name=dvdmovieguide>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdmg.com/simpsonsseasoneight.shtml|title=The Simpsons: The Complete Eighth Season (1995)|last=Jacobson|first=Colin|publisher=DVD Movie Guide|date=January 5, 2006|access-date=December 1, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n;Bibliography\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Turner|first=Chris|author-link=Chris Turner (author)|title=Planet Simpson: How a Cartoon Masterpiece Documented an Era and Defined a Generation|title-link=Planet Simpson|others=Foreword by [[Douglas Coupland]]|edition=1st|year=2004|location=Toronto|publisher=[[Random House Canada]]|oclc=55682258|isbn=978-0-679-31318-2|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|The_Simpsons/Season_8#My_Sister.2C_My_Sitter|\"My Sister, My Sitter\"}}\n{{portal|The Simpsons}}\n*[http://www.thesimpsons.com/#/recaps/season-8_episode-17 \"My Sister, My Sitter\"] at The Simpsons.com\n*{{Snpp capsule|4F13}}\n*{{imdb episode|0779672}}\n*{{tv.com episode|the-simpsons/my-sister-my-sitter-1455}}\n\n{{The Simpsons episodes|8}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n[[Category:The Simpsons (season 8) episodes]]\n[[Category:1997 American television episodes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox Simpsons episode\n| title      = My Sister, My Sitter\n| image      = \n| caption    = \n| season     = 8\n| episode    = 17\n| director   = [[Jim Reardon]]<ref name=\"bbc\"/>\n| writer     = [[Dan Greaney]]<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/simpsons/episodeguide/season8/page17.shtml|title=My Sister, My Sitter|access-date=May 2, 2007|last1=Martyn|first1=Warren|last2=Wood|first2=Adrian|year=2000|publisher=BBC}}</ref>\n| production = 4F13\n| airdate    = {{start date|1997|03|02}}<ref name=\"officialsite\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thesimpsons.com/#/recaps/season-8_episode-17|title=My Sister, My Sitter|access-date=May 2, 2007|publisher=The Simpsons.com}}</ref>\n| couch_gag  = The living room is on a ship being tossed by a stormy ocean. The Simpsons, decked out in raingear, run to the couch, but get washed away by a large wave.<ref name=\"bbc\"/>\n| commentary = [[Matt Groening]]<br>[[Josh Weinstein]]<br>Molly Weinstein<br>Simon Weinstein<br>[[Yeardley Smith]]<br>[[Jim Reardon]]<br>[[George Meyer]]\n| prev       = [[Brother from Another Series]]\n| next       = [[Homer vs. the Eighteenth Amendment]]\n}}\n\"'''My Sister, My Sitter'''\" is the seventeenth episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki> [[The Simpsons (season 8)|eighth season]]. It originally aired on the [[Fox network]] in the United States on March 2, 1997. In the episode, Marge and Homer leave Lisa to babysit Bart and Maggie. Annoyed that his younger sister is his babysitter, Bart does everything he can to annoy her. When Bart is injured, Lisa must find him medical attention without spoiling her reputation as a good babysitter.\n\nThe episode was written by [[Dan Greaney]] and directed by [[Jim Reardon]]. The script was written to focus on the relationship between Bart and Lisa and the episode has further been used{{by whom?|date=March 2020}} to discuss the difficulties in letting children babysit themselves. The episode received mostly positive reviews.\n\n==Plot==\nInspired by ''[[The Baby-Sitters Club]]'' series of novels, [[Lisa Simpson|Lisa]] decides to become a babysitter, but no one takes her seriously because of her age. When [[Maude Flanders|Maude]] is taken hostage in Lebanon, [[Ned Flanders|Ned]] must leave suddenly to get her released. In his haste, he agrees to let Lisa babysit [[Rod and Todd Flanders|Rod and Todd]]. Ned puts out the good word for Lisa, who experiences a business boom.\n\nInspired by the success of [[Baltimore]]'s [[Inner Harbor|revamped wharf]], the [[Springfield (The Simpsons)|Springfield]] Squidport reopens and throws a gala. [[Homer Simpson|Homer]] and [[Marge Simpson|Marge]] attend, leaving Lisa to babysit [[Bart Simpson|Bart]] and [[Maggie Simpson|Maggie]]. Bart is upset that his younger sister is his babysitter; Lisa thinks his childish antics warrant it. Bart torments Lisa by having a giant [[submarine sandwich]] delivered, hiring [[Krusty the Clown|Krusty]] for a bachelor party, claiming that Lisa saw a [[UFO]], dialing {{nobr|9-1-1}} for a \"sisterectomy\", and feeding Maggie coffee ice cream for dinner.\n\nBart's pranks anger Lisa so much that she lunges at him, causing him to fall down the stairs, dislocating his shoulder and causing a large bump on his head. Bart realizes if Lisa fails to take him to a nearby hospital, her reputation as a babysitter will be ruined. To make his condition worse, Bart locks himself in his room and repeatedly hits his head on the door, eventually knocking himself unconscious. \n\nLisa tries to call for an ambulance, but the {{nobr|9-1-1}} operator refuses to assist her due to Bart's earlier prank calls. Lisa considers asking [[Dr. Hibbert]] for help, but realizes that would ruin her reputation as a babysitter. Instead she takes Bart to [[Dr. Nick Riviera]]'s clinic in a wheelbarrow, bringing Maggie along in a [[pet carrier]] because the coffee ice cream has overstimulated her. Lisa is unable to see the doctor due to a long queue in the waiting room.\n\nFrantic, Lisa tries to wheel Bart and Maggie to the hospital. She loses control of the wheelbarrow and it rolls down a cliff into a muddy river &mdash; in front of aghast onlookers at the Squidport. The crowd assumes Lisa is on drugs, has murdered Bart, and is about to drown the caged Maggie. Lisa reveals none of the crowd's suspicions are true, but her reputation is ruined.\n\nLater Bart, whose injuries have been treated, apologizes to Lisa for causing the ordeal and ruining her babysitting business. She forgives him, but feels bad for being called the \"World's Worst Babysitter\". Much to her delight, she receives babysitting requests from Dr. Hibbert and Ned Flanders because they cannot find any other sitters.\n\n==Production and themes==\n[[File:USS-Constellation-Szmurlo.jpg|thumb|The Squidport was inspired by waterfront renovations such as [[Harborplace]] in [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]].]]\nThe episode was directed by [[Jim Reardon]] and written by [[Dan Greaney]].<ref name=\"bbc\"/> Like numerous preceding episodes, \"My Sister, My Sitter\" deals with the relationship between Bart and Lisa. Greaney specializes in writing Bart and Lisa episodes from the perspective of a kid.<ref name=\"Weinstein\">{{cite AV media|last=Weinstein|first=Josh|date=2006|title=Commentary for \"My Sister, My Sitter\". The Simpsons: The Complete Eighth Season|medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref> Elaine E Sutherland, who is a member of the Law Society of Scotland's Family Law Sub-Committee and Professor of Child and Family Law at the Law School, Stirling University, used the episode to describe the potential problems of letting one of your kids babysit the rest. While one child may be mature enough to babysit, it is not certain that the other kids accept the babysitter's authority.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edinburghnews.scotsman.com/opinion/Elaine-Sutherland-A-parents-guide.6816766.jp|title=Elaine Sutherland: A parent's guide to choosing who looks after baby|last=Sutherland|first=Elaine|work=Edinburgh Evening News|date=August 11, 2011|access-date=September 5, 2011}}</ref> According to Alan S. Brown and Chris Logan, the writers of the book ''[[The Psychology of The Simpsons|The Psychology of the Simpsons: D\u2019oh!]]'', the episode is an example of how feminine anger rarely solves the problem on ''The Simpsons''. \u201cHere, Lisa\u2019s rage and ongoing frustration contribute to her difficulty in making good decisions about what to do with her emotion,\u201d they write.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Brown|first1=Alan|last2=Logan|first2=Chris|year=2006|title=The Psychology of The Simpsons|title-link=The Psychology of The Simpsons|pages=114\u2013115|isbn=1-932100-70-9}}</ref> Keeping with the babysitter theme, there are cultural references to ''[[The Baby-Sitters Club]]'': Lisa reads book #14 - The Formula Formula, while Janey is on book #20 - The President's Baby Is Missing.<ref name=\"bbc\"/>\n\nThe idea of revamping the waterfront came from cities like [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]], who were always trying to fix formerly horrible places.<ref name=\"Weinstein\"/> [[Chris Turner (author)|Chris Turner]], the author of the book ''[[Planet Simpson]]'', writes about the scene at the Squidport: \"The \"satirical\" setting seems almost documentary\". The Squidport is a local revitalization project, which recast a historic industrial area as a pedestrian mall. He calls this an example of how \u201chyper-consumer culture of Springfield moves front and center\u201d{{sfn|Turner|2004|p=106}} On the waterfront, Rainier Wolfcastle opens a restaurant called \"Planet Hype\".{{sfn|Turner|2004|p=106}} This is a parody of the international theme restaurant franchise [[Planet Hollywood]].<ref name=\"Weinstein\" /> Wolfcastle is a parody of [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]],{{sfn|Turner|2004|p=385}} who launched Planet Hollywood along with Sylvester Stallone, Bruce Willis, Demi Moore and Whoopi Goldberg in 1991.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/id/2086889/|title=Arnold's Bad Business|author=Gross, Daniel|work=Slate|date=August 11, 2003|access-date=September 5, 2011}}</ref> According to [[Matt Groening]], the show had written an entire episode around Planet Hollywood, which featured the voices of Schwarzenegger, Stallone, and Willis as [[The Three Stooges]] type of characters. The episode was never animated, because it turned out that it was only the publicist of Planet Hollywood's idea and the actors did not want to participate.<ref>{{cite AV media|last=Groening|first=Matt|date=2006|title=Commentary for \"My Sister, My Sitter\". The Simpsons: The Complete Eighth Season|medium=DVD|publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nIn its original broadcast, \"My Sister, My Sitter\" finished 47th in ratings in a tie with ''[[Melrose Place]]'' for the week of February 24 \u2013 March 2, 1997, with a [[Nielsen ratings|Nielsen rating]] of 9.0, equivalent to approximately 8.7 million viewing households. It was the fifth highest-rated show on the Fox network that week.<ref>{{cite news|title=Prime-time ratings|work=The Orange County Register|page=F02|date=March 5, 1997}}</ref> \n\nSince airing, the episode has received mostly positive reviews from television critics. The authors of the book ''I Can't Believe It's a Bigger and Better Updated Unofficial Simpsons Guide'', Warren Martyn and Adrian Wood, called it \"a clever episode, if a little disjointed&nbsp;\u2014 the two stories don't gel as well as normal.\"<ref name=\"bbc\"/> \n\nTim Raynor of DVDTown.com said that the episode \"is full of the usual, fun antics that you would expect from Bart or any of the other dumb Simpsons.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdtown.com/reviews/dvd-simpsons-the-the-complete-8th-season/3886|title=Simpsons, The: The Complete 8th Season (DVD)|last=Raynor|first=Tim|date=August 21, 2006|publisher=DVDTown.com|access-date=April 23, 2009|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928084257/http://www.dvdtown.com/reviews/dvd-simpsons-the-the-complete-8th-season/3886|archive-date=September 28, 2011}}</ref> \n\nDVD Movie Guide's Colin Jacobson said that \"the segments in which Lisa babysits the various kids in town are a delight\" and that the episode \"mixes wacky moments with reality as it places Lisa in a logical position. Her conflict with Bart creates realism and also brings out the comedy.\"<ref name=dvdmovieguide>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdmg.com/simpsonsseasoneight.shtml|title=The Simpsons: The Complete Eighth Season (1995)|last=Jacobson|first=Colin|publisher=DVD Movie Guide|date=January 5, 2006|access-date=December 1, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n;Bibliography\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Turner|first=Chris|author-link=Chris Turner (author)|title=Planet Simpson: How a Cartoon Masterpiece Documented an Era and Defined a Generation|title-link=Planet Simpson|others=Foreword by [[Douglas Coupland]]|edition=1st|year=2004|location=Toronto|publisher=[[Random House Canada]]|oclc=55682258|isbn=978-0-679-31318-2|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|The_Simpsons/Season_8#My_Sister.2C_My_Sitter|\"My Sister, My Sitter\"}}\n{{portal|The Simpsons}}\n*[http://www.thesimpsons.com/#/recaps/season-8_episode-17 \"My Sister, My Sitter\"] at The Simpsons.com\n*{{Snpp capsule|4F13}}\n*{{imdb episode|0779672}}\n*{{tv.com episode|the-simpsons/my-sister-my-sitter-1455}}\n\n{{The Simpsons episodes|8}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n[[Category:The Simpsons (season 8) episodes]]\n[[Category:1997 American television episodes]]\n", "name_user": "2001:569:bd5a:3100:b9c1:c5cf:f51e:9ae1", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/My_Sister,_My_Sitter"}
{"title_page": "Will Poulter", "text_new": "{{short description|British actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Will Poulter\n| image              = Will Poulter 2016 3.jpg\n| caption            = Poulter at the Paris premiere of ''[[The Revenant (2015 film)|The Revenant]]'' in 2016\n| birth_name         = William Jack Poulter\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1993|1|28}}\n| birth_place        = [[Hammersmith]], [[London]], England\n| nationality        = British\n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 2007\u2013present\n}}\n'''William Jack Poulter''' is an English actor. He first gained recognition for his role as [[Eustace Scrubb]] in the fantasy adventure film ''[[The Chronicles of Narnia: The Voyage of the Dawn Treader]]'' (2010). Poulter received further praise for his starring role in the comedy film ''[[We're the Millers]]'' (2013), for which he won the [[BAFTA Rising Star Award]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-26218678 \"Bafta Film Awards 2014: Full list of winners\"]. [[BBC]]. 16 February 2014</ref>\n\nPoulter also starred in the science fiction film ''[[The Maze Runner (film)|The Maze Runner]]'' (2014), the period epic film ''[[The Revenant (2015 film)|The Revenant]]'' (2015), the crime drama film ''[[Detroit (film)|Detroit]]'' (2017), the interactive science fiction film ''[[Black Mirror: Bandersnatch]]'' (2018), and the folk horror film ''[[Midsommar (film)|Midsommar]]'' (2019).\n\n==Early life==\nPoulter was born in Hammersmith, London, England, the son of Caroline (n\u00e9e Barrah), a former nurse, and Neil Poulter, a distinguished physician and Professor of Preventive Cardiovascular Medicine at [[Imperial College London]].<ref>{{web cite|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/people/n.poulter|title=PROFESSOR NEIL POULTER|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"rambow\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/3672031/Son-of-Rambow-ready-for-action.html Son of Rambow: ready for action] at www.telegraph.co.uk (accessed 22 June 2008)</ref> His mother was raised in [[Kenya]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flaunt.com/content/people/will-poulter-detroit-movie|title=Will Poulter|website=Flaunt Magazine}}</ref> He struggled in school due to [[dyslexia]] and [[developmental coordination disorder]], telling ''[[The Independent]]'' in 2013, \"It felt like it didn't matter how hard I tried, I wasn't getting anywhere. That's the most demoralising thing, as a kid. And to find something like drama, which I loved so much\u2026 it gave me a sense of purpose.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/the-big-picture-how-will-poulter-shook-off-the-tough-tearaway-tag-to-become-hollywoods-latest-8779097.html|title=The big picture: How Will Poulter shook off the tough tearaway tag to become Hollywood's latest loveable dork|last=|first=|date=2013-08-25|website=The Independent|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2007\u20132012: Early work===\nPoulter played various acting roles before landing the role of Lee Carter in the 2007 movie ''[[Son of Rambow]]'', which was released to positive reviews, and praise for the performances of Poulter and his co-star [[Bill Milner]]. He also performed with other young comedic actors in ''[[School of Comedy]]'',<ref name=\"thelist\">{{cite news|url=http://edinburghfestival.list.co.uk/article/3954-school-of-comedy|title=School of Comedy|last=Lee|first=Robin|date=16 August 2007|work=[[The List (magazine)|The List]]|accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref> which aired its pilot on Channel 4's [[Comedy Lab]] on 21 August 2008. ''School of Comedy'' was then commissioned for a full series by [[Channel 4]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/comedy-lab|title=Comedy Lab: Comedy Lab|website=Channel 4}}</ref> which began airing on 2 October 2009. The programme finished after a second series.\n\nIn 2009, he was selected to play the role of [[Eustace Scrubb]] in the film ''[[The Chronicles of Narnia: The Voyage of the Dawn Treader]]'' (filmed in Queensland, Australia), and was accompanied by some members of his family. The movie was first screened on 10 December 2010. The film opened to mixed reviews, but Poulter's performance was well received.<ref name=\"narnia\">[http://www.narniaweb.com/news.asp?id=1878&dl=20066430 Will Poulter Cast as Eustace Scrubb] at www.narniaweb.com (accessed 22 June 2008)</ref><ref name=\"narnia3\">[http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=46179 Will Poulter Cast in Narnia 3] at www.comingsoon.net (accessed 22 June 2008</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he appeared in the [[BBC Three]] pilot ''The Fades'', a 60-minute supernatural thriller written by ''[[Skins (TV series)|Skins]]'' writer [[Jack Thorne (writer)|Jack Thorne]]. The pilot was picked up as a six-part series with an almost entirely new cast, [[The Fades (TV series)|which aired]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://screenterrier.blogspot.com/2010/06/fades.html |title=ScreenTerrier: The Fades |publisher=Screenterrier.blogspot.com |date=5 June 2010 |accessdate=17 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108090440/http://screenterrier.blogspot.com/2010/06/fades.html |archivedate=8 January 2014  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sibayan |first=Genevieve |url=http://frostmagazine.com/2010/08/touch-a-new-supernatural-drama-series-for-bbc3-tv/2441 |title=Touch \u2013 A new supernatural drama series for BBC3 {TV} |publisher=Frost Magazine |date= |accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nPoulter began filming a small British independent film called ''[[Wild Bill (2011 film)|Wild Bill]]'', directed by [[Dexter Fletcher]], at the end of 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehollywoodnews.com/2010/11/09/narnia-stars-switch-londons-christmas-lights/ |title=Narnia stars switch on London's Christmas lights! |publisher=The Hollywood News |date=9 November 2010 |accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref> It centres around Bill Hayward, played by [[Charlie Creed-Miles]], who, on parole after spending eight years in prison, finds his two sons, Dean (Poulter) and Jimmy (Sammy Williams), living alone and abandoned by their mother. With the attention of social services now focused on the boys, Bill struggles to play good dad while keeping out of jail as Jimmy gets in trouble with some dangerous acquaintances of Bill's past.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://wildbillthefilm.com/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=24 May 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110902102414/http://wildbillthefilm.com/ |archive-date=2 September 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The film was released on 23 March 2012 to extremely positive reviews, with praise for Poulter's performance.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://willpoulterfans.webs.com/apps/blog/show/8106802-approximate-release-date-for-wild-bill |title=Approximate Release Date for Wild Bill \u2013 The Unofficial Will Poulter Fansite |publisher=Willpoulterfans.webs.com |date=25 July 2011 |accessdate=17 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121101091818/http://willpoulterfans.webs.com/apps/blog/show/8106802-approximate-release-date-for-wild-bill |archive-date=1 November 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> In 2011, Poulter appeared with the popular British blogger and his [[School of Comedy]] co-star [[Jack Harries]] on his YouTube channel by the name of ''JacksGap'' in a video called ''Jack and Will''.\n\n===2013\u2013present: Mainstream recognition and further work===\n[[File:Will Poulter 2013.jpg|thumb|left|Poulter at the London premiere of ''[[We're the Millers]]'' in August 2013]]\nIn 2013, he played Kenny in ''[[We're the Millers]]'', starring [[Jennifer Aniston]] and [[Jason Sudeikis]]. While the film opened to mixed reviews, the performances of the cast were well received, especially that of Poulter, who found mainstream recognition with his showy, comedic work in the film. He also appeared as a caretaker in the music video for [[Rizzle Kicks]]' song \"Skip to the Good Bit\". Though he loved the script and auditioned for the role of Augustus Waters, he was denied the part in ''[[The Fault in Our Stars (film)|The Fault in Our Stars]]''.<ref name=\"RevealingInterview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/will-poulter-detroit-interview-calvin-klein-jeans-first-look|title=Detroit's Will Poulter Talks Making Out with Jennifer Aniston and Being Miserable with Leonardo DiCaprio|first=Anna Peele, Mei|last=Tao|date=20 December 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, he played Fordy in the crime film ''[[Plastic (2014 film)|Plastic]]'', directed by [[Julian Gilbey]] and starring [[Ed Speleers]], [[Alfie Allen]], [[Sebastian De Souza]] and [[Emma Rigby]]. The film was critically panned on release. The same year, he played Gally in the film adaptation of ''[[The Maze Runner (film)|The Maze Runner]]'', alongside [[Dylan O'Brien]] and [[Kaya Scodelario]]. The film was a critical and commercial success, with the performances of the cast being praised. Poulter went on to describe the film, and his role in it, as \"a turning point\" in his career.<ref name=\"RevealingInterview\"/>\n\nIn 2015, Poulter starred as Shane in the Irish indie film ''[[Glassland]]'', directed by Gerard Barrett and co-starring [[Jack Reynor]] and [[Toni Collette]]. The film was a critical success, with many reviewers praising Poulter's performance in particular as being his most diverse role to date. In an interview with [[BBC Radio 1]], Poulter stated the film was \"the proudest I've been to be a part of a movie\".\n\n[[File:Will Poulter SDCC 2014.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Poulter in 2014]]\n\nIn 2014, Poulter won the [[BAFTA Rising Star Award]], voted for by the public.<ref name=risingstar>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-26218678|title=Bafta Film Awards 2014: Full list of winners|publisher=BBC|date=16 February 2014|accessdate=9 March 2014}}</ref> Other actors nominated for the award were [[Lupita Nyong'o]], [[George MacKay (actor)|George MacKay]], [[L\u00e9a Seydoux]] and [[Dane DeHaan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a541988/bafta-film-awards-2014-nominations-in-full.html|title=BAFTA Film Awards 2014 \u2013 nominations in full|last=Reynolds|first=Simon|author2=Harris, Jamie |date=8 January 2014|work=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=8 January 2014}}</ref> The same year, he also won the [[MTV Movie Award for Best Breakthrough Performance]] and the [[MTV Movie Award for Best Kiss]] (shared with his co-stars [[Jennifer Aniston]] and [[Emma Roberts]]) for his performance in ''[[We're the Millers]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2014/04/13/will-poulter-emma-roberts-jennifer-aniston-win-mtv-movie-award-best-kiss-2014/|title=Will Poulter, Emma Roberts & Jennifer Aniston Win MTV Best Kiss|date=13 April 2014|work=Hollywood life|accessdate=24 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Poulter was chosen as one of 23 upcoming actors to feature in July's issue of [[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]], with all actors being named \"Hollywood's Next Wave\". Other actors featured included [[Dylan O'Brien]] (Poulter's co-star in ''The Maze Runner'' series) and [[Jack Reynor]] (Poulter's co-star in ''Glassland'', ''Detroit'', and ''Midsommar'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/vf-hollywood/up-and-coming-actors-jaden-willow-smith|title=Hollywood's Next Wave|last=Smith|first=Krista|date=11 June 2014|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|accessdate=24 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nPoulter played [[Jim Bridger]] in the revenge-thriller ''[[The Revenant (2015 film)|The Revenant]]'', directed by [[Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu]], and starring [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] and [[Tom Hardy]]. The film centers on an 1820s frontiersman on a path of vengeance against those who left him for dead after a bear mauling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/2014/film/news/will-poulter-revenant-leonardo-dicaprio-1201190212|title=We\u2019re the Millers\" Will Poulter Joins Leonardo DiCaprio in \u2018The Revenant\u2019 (Exclusive)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=25 June 2014|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref> In 2017, he played the racist police officer Philip Krauss in the film ''[[Detroit (film)|Detroit]]'', about the [[1967 Detroit riots]]. His work in the film was praised with one critic calling him \"terrifyingly confident\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metro.us/entertainment/movies/detroit-review-kathryn-bigelow-john-boyega|title='Detroit' is a nightmarish history lesson about trauma|last=Prigge|first=Matt|date=23 July 2017|website=Metro|access-date=4 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nPoulter was initially cast as Pennywise the Clown in the [[It (2017 film)|2017 remake]] of the [[Stephen King]] miniseries ''[[It (1990 film)|It]]''. However, it was announced in June 2016 that [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]] had been cast instead because Poulter dropped out due both to scheduling conflicts (the film was set to shoot at the same time as Poulter was set to begin work on ''Detroit'') as well as the departure of its initial director, Cary Fukunaga.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-adaptation-finds-pennywise-898993 |title=Stephen King's 'It' Adaptation Finds Its Pennywise the Clown (Exclusive) |publisher=Hollywood Reporter |date=2 June 2016 |accessdate=22 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Poulter reprised his role as Gally in ''[[Maze Runner: The Death Cure]]'', the third and final installment of the ''Maze Runner'' film series. Later that year, he starred in the film ''[[The Little Stranger (film)|The Little Stranger]]'' as Roderick \"Roddy\" Ayres, a facially disfigured, haunted war veteran, and as game developer Colin Ritman in ''[[Black Mirror: Bandersnatch]]'', a standalone [[Interactive movie|interactive film]] of the ''Black Mirror'' television series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2018-12-31/bandersnatch-cast-black-mirror/|title=Meet the cast of Black Mirror's interactive film Bandersnatch|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=31 December 2018}}</ref> In 2019, he played the character of Mark in [[Ari Aster]]\u2019s horror film ''[[Midsommar (film)|Midsommar]]''.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Son of Rambow]]''\n| Lee Carter\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[The Chronicles of Narnia: The Voyage of the Dawn Treader]]''\n| [[Eustace Scrubb]]\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Wild Bill (2011 film)|Wild Bill]]''\n| Dean\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[We're the Millers]]''\n| Kenny Rossmore / Kenny Miller\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2014\n| ''[[Plastic (2014 film)|Plastic]]''\n| Fordy\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Maze Runner (film)|The Maze Runner]]''\n| Gally\n|\n|-\n|''A Plea For Grimsby''\n|Jone\n|\n|-\n|''[[Glassland]]''\n| Shane\n| \n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[The Revenant (2015 film)|The Revenant]]''\n| [[Jim Bridger]]\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Kids in Love (film)|Kids in Love]]''\n| Jack\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2017\n| ''[[War Machine (film)|War Machine]]''\n| Sgt. Rick Ortega\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Detroit (film)|Detroit]]''\n| Philip Krauss\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2018\n| ''[[Maze Runner: The Death Cure]]''\n| Gally\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Little Stranger (film)|The Little Stranger]]''\n| Roderick \"Roddy\" Ayres\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2019\n|''Bainne''\n|Irish farmer\n|\n|-\n|''[[Midsommar (film)|Midsommar]]''\n| Mark\n|\n|}\n\n===Series===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|2007\n|''Comedy: Shuffle''\n|Find Your Folks Presenter \n|2 episodes\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Comedy Lab]]''\n|Various\n|Episode: \"Kids School of Comedy\"\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Lead Balloon]]''\n|Sweet Throwing Boy\n|Episode: \"Nuts\"\n|-\n|2009\u20132010\n|''[[School of Comedy]]''\n|various characters\n|8 episodes; also writer\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[The Fades (TV series)|The Fades]]''\n|Mac\n|Episode: \"Pilot\"\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Black Mirror]]''\n|Colin Ritman\n|Episode: \"[[Black Mirror: Bandersnatch|Bandersnatch]]\"\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''The Dark Pictures Anthology: Little Hope''\n| Andrew\n| Motion capture\n|}<br />\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=August 2019}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Year\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Work\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Award\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Category\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Result\n|-\n|2008\n|rowspan=\"2\"|''[[Son of Rambow]]''\n|[[British Independent Film Awards 2008|British Independent Film Awards]]\n|[[British Independent Film Awards 2008#Most Promising Newcomer|Most Promising Newcomer]]\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|2009\n|[[30th Young Artist Awards|Young Artist Awards]]\n|[[30th Young Artist Awards#Best Performance in an International Feature Film|Best Performance in an International Feature Film \u2013 Leading Young Performers]] <small>(shared with [[Bill Milner]])</small>\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|2010\n|rowspan=4|''[[The Chronicles of Narnia: The Voyage of the Dawn Treader]]''\n|Phoenix Film Critics Society\n|Best Performance by a Youth in a Leading or Supporting Role \u2013 Male\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2011\n|[[32nd Young Artist Awards|Young Artist Awards]]\n|Best Performance in a Feature Film \u2013 Young Ensemble Cast <small>(shared with [[Georgie Henley]] and [[Skandar Keynes]])</small>\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|[[Academy of Science Fiction, Fantasy and Horror Films]]\n|Best Performance by a Younger Actor\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|[[London Film Critics' Circle]]\n|Young British Performer of the Year\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Wild Bill (2011 film)|Wild Bill]]''\n|London Film Critics' Circle\n|Young British Performer of the Year\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|rowspan=6|2014\n|rowspan=6|''[[We're the Millers]]''\n|[[2014 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards]]\n|Choice Movie Liplock <small>(shared with [[Emma Roberts]] and [[Jennifer Aniston]])</small>\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[2014 MTV Movie Awards|MTV Movie Awards]]\n|[[2014 MTV Movie Awards#Breakthrough Performance|Breakthrough Performance]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[2014 MTV Movie Awards#Best Kiss|Best Kiss]] <small>(shared with [[Emma Roberts]] and [[Jennifer Aniston]])</small>\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[2014 MTV Movie Awards#Best Musical Moment|Best Musical Moment]]\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|[[67th British Academy Film Awards|British Academy Film Awards]]\n|[[BAFTA Rising Star Award|EE Rising Star Award]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Empire Awards]]\n|[[Empire Award for Best Male Newcomer|Best Male Newcomer]]\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[The Maze Runner (film)|The Maze Runner]]''\n|MTV Movie Awards\n|[[MTV Movie Award for Best Fight|Best Fight]] <small>(shared with [[Dylan O'Brien]])</small>\n|{{won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|2401020}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Will Poulter\n| list =\n{{BAFTA Rising Star Award}}\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best Fight}}\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best Kiss}}\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best Breakthrough Performance}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Poulter, William}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:English male child actors]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (people)]]\n[[Category:BAFTA Rising Star Award winners]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:People educated at The Harrodian School]]\n[[Category:People from Hammersmith]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People with dyslexia]]\n[[Category:People with developmental coordination disorder]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Will Poulter\n| image              = Will Poulter 2016 3.jpg\n| caption            = Poulter at the Paris premiere of ''[[The Revenant (2015 film)|The Revenant]]'' in 2016\n| birth_name         = William Jack Poulter\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1993|1|28}}\n| birth_place        = [[Hammersmith]], [[London]], England\n| nationality        = British\n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 2007\u2013present\n}}\n'''William Jack Poulter''' is an English actor. He first gained recognition for his role as [[Eustace Scrubb]] in the fantasy adventure film ''[[The Chronicles of Narnia: The Voyage of the Dawn Treader]]'' (2010). Poulter received further praise for his starring role in the comedy film ''[[We're the Millers]]'' (2013), for which he won the [[BAFTA Rising Star Award]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-26218678 \"Bafta Film Awards 2014: Full list of winners\"]. [[BBC]]. 16 February 2014</ref>\n\nPoulter also starred in the science fiction film ''[[The Maze Runner (film)|The Maze Runner]]'' (2014), the period epic film ''[[The Revenant (2015 film)|The Revenant]]'' (2015), the crime drama film ''[[Detroit (film)|Detroit]]'' (2017), the interactive science fiction film ''[[Black Mirror: Bandersnatch]]'' (2018), and the folk horror film ''[[Midsommar (film)|Midsommar]]'' (2019).\n\n==Early life==\nPoulter was born in Hammersmith, London, England, the son of Caroline (n\u00e9e Barrah), a former nurse, and Neil Poulter, a distinguished physician and Professor of Preventive Cardiovascular Medicine at [[Imperial College London]].<ref>{{web cite|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/people/n.poulter|title=PROFESSOR NEIL POULTER|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"rambow\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/3672031/Son-of-Rambow-ready-for-action.html Son of Rambow: ready for action] at www.telegraph.co.uk (accessed 22 June 2008)</ref> His mother was raised in [[Kenya]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flaunt.com/content/people/will-poulter-detroit-movie|title=Will Poulter|website=Flaunt Magazine}}</ref> He struggled in school due to [[dyslexia]] and [[developmental coordination disorder]], telling ''[[The Independent]]'' in 2013, \"It felt like it didn't matter how hard I tried, I wasn't getting anywhere. That's the most demoralising thing, as a kid. And to find something like drama, which I loved so much\u2026 it gave me a sense of purpose.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/the-big-picture-how-will-poulter-shook-off-the-tough-tearaway-tag-to-become-hollywoods-latest-8779097.html|title=The big picture: How Will Poulter shook off the tough tearaway tag to become Hollywood's latest loveable dork|last=|first=|date=2013-08-25|website=The Independent|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2007\u20132012: Early work===\nPoulter played various acting roles before landing the role of Lee Carter in the 2007 movie ''[[Son of Rambow]]'', which was released to positive reviews, and praise for the performances of Poulter and his co-star [[Bill Milner]]. He also performed with other young comedic actors in ''[[School of Comedy]]'',<ref name=\"thelist\">{{cite news|url=http://edinburghfestival.list.co.uk/article/3954-school-of-comedy|title=School of Comedy|last=Lee|first=Robin|date=16 August 2007|work=[[The List (magazine)|The List]]|accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref> which aired its pilot on Channel 4's [[Comedy Lab]] on 21 August 2008. ''School of Comedy'' was then commissioned for a full series by [[Channel 4]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/comedy-lab|title=Comedy Lab: Comedy Lab|website=Channel 4}}</ref> which began airing on 2 October 2009. The programme finished after a second series.\n\nIn 2009, he was selected to play the role of [[Eustace Scrubb]] in the film ''[[The Chronicles of Narnia: The Voyage of the Dawn Treader]]'' (filmed in Queensland, Australia), and was accompanied by some members of his family. The movie was first screened on 10 December 2010. The film opened to mixed reviews, but Poulter's performance was well received.<ref name=\"narnia\">[http://www.narniaweb.com/news.asp?id=1878&dl=20066430 Will Poulter Cast as Eustace Scrubb] at www.narniaweb.com (accessed 22 June 2008)</ref><ref name=\"narnia3\">[http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=46179 Will Poulter Cast in Narnia 3] at www.comingsoon.net (accessed 22 June 2008</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he appeared in the [[BBC Three]] pilot ''The Fades'', a 60-minute supernatural thriller written by ''[[Skins (TV series)|Skins]]'' writer [[Jack Thorne (writer)|Jack Thorne]]. The pilot was picked up as a six-part series with an almost entirely new cast, [[The Fades (TV series)|which aired]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://screenterrier.blogspot.com/2010/06/fades.html |title=ScreenTerrier: The Fades |publisher=Screenterrier.blogspot.com |date=5 June 2010 |accessdate=17 April 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108090440/http://screenterrier.blogspot.com/2010/06/fades.html |archivedate=8 January 2014  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sibayan |first=Genevieve |url=http://frostmagazine.com/2010/08/touch-a-new-supernatural-drama-series-for-bbc3-tv/2441 |title=Touch \u2013 A new supernatural drama series for BBC3 {TV} |publisher=Frost Magazine |date= |accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nPoulter began filming a small British independent film called ''[[Wild Bill (2011 film)|Wild Bill]]'', directed by [[Dexter Fletcher]], at the end of 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehollywoodnews.com/2010/11/09/narnia-stars-switch-londons-christmas-lights/ |title=Narnia stars switch on London's Christmas lights! |publisher=The Hollywood News |date=9 November 2010 |accessdate=17 April 2013}}</ref> It centres around Bill Hayward, played by [[Charlie Creed-Miles]], who, on parole after spending eight years in prison, finds his two sons, Dean (Poulter) and Jimmy (Sammy Williams), living alone and abandoned by their mother. With the attention of social services now focused on the boys, Bill struggles to play good dad while keeping out of jail as Jimmy gets in trouble with some dangerous acquaintances of Bill's past.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://wildbillthefilm.com/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=24 May 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110902102414/http://wildbillthefilm.com/ |archive-date=2 September 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> The film was released on 23 March 2012 to extremely positive reviews, with praise for Poulter's performance.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://willpoulterfans.webs.com/apps/blog/show/8106802-approximate-release-date-for-wild-bill |title=Approximate Release Date for Wild Bill \u2013 The Unofficial Will Poulter Fansite |publisher=Willpoulterfans.webs.com |date=25 July 2011 |accessdate=17 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121101091818/http://willpoulterfans.webs.com/apps/blog/show/8106802-approximate-release-date-for-wild-bill |archive-date=1 November 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> In 2011, Poulter appeared with the popular British blogger and his [[School of Comedy]] co-star [[Jack Harries]] on his YouTube channel by the name of ''JacksGap'' in a video called ''Jack and Will''.\n\n===2013\u2013present: Mainstream recognition and further work===\n[[File:Will Poulter 2013.jpg|thumb|left|Poulter at the London premiere of ''[[We're the Millers]]'' in August 2013]]\nIn 2013, he played Kenny in ''[[We're the Millers]]'', starring [[Jennifer Aniston]] and [[Jason Sudeikis]]. While the film opened to mixed reviews, the performances of the cast were well received, especially that of Poulter, who found mainstream recognition with his showy, comedic work in the film. He also appeared as a caretaker in the music video for [[Rizzle Kicks]]' song \"Skip to the Good Bit\". Though he loved the script and auditioned for the role of Augustus Waters, he was denied the part in ''[[The Fault in Our Stars (film)|The Fault in Our Stars]]''.<ref name=\"RevealingInterview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/will-poulter-detroit-interview-calvin-klein-jeans-first-look|title=Detroit's Will Poulter Talks Making Out with Jennifer Aniston and Being Miserable with Leonardo DiCaprio|first=Anna Peele, Mei|last=Tao|date=20 December 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, he played Fordy in the crime film ''[[Plastic (2014 film)|Plastic]]'', directed by [[Julian Gilbey]] and starring [[Ed Speleers]], [[Alfie Allen]], [[Sebastian De Souza]] and [[Emma Rigby]]. The film was critically panned on release. The same year, he played Gally in the film adaptation of ''[[The Maze Runner (film)|The Maze Runner]]'', alongside [[Dylan O'Brien]] and [[Kaya Scodelario]]. The film was a critical and commercial success, with the performances of the cast being praised. Poulter went on to describe the film, and his role in it, as \"a turning point\" in his career.<ref name=\"RevealingInterview\"/>\n\nIn 2015, Poulter starred as Shane in the Irish indie film ''[[Glassland]]'', directed by Gerard Barrett and co-starring [[Jack Reynor]] and [[Toni Collette]]. The film was a critical success, with many reviewers praising Poulter's performance in particular as being his most diverse role to date. In an interview with [[BBC Radio 1]], Poulter stated the film was \"the proudest I've been to be a part of a movie\".\n\n[[File:Will Poulter SDCC 2014.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Poulter in 2014]]\n\nIn 2014, Poulter won the [[BAFTA Rising Star Award]], voted for by the public.<ref name=risingstar>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-26218678|title=Bafta Film Awards 2014: Full list of winners|publisher=BBC|date=16 February 2014|accessdate=9 March 2014}}</ref> Other actors nominated for the award were [[Lupita Nyong'o]], [[George MacKay (actor)|George MacKay]], [[L\u00e9a Seydoux]] and [[Dane DeHaan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a541988/bafta-film-awards-2014-nominations-in-full.html|title=BAFTA Film Awards 2014 \u2013 nominations in full|last=Reynolds|first=Simon|author2=Harris, Jamie |date=8 January 2014|work=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=8 January 2014}}</ref> The same year, he also won the [[MTV Movie Award for Best Breakthrough Performance]] and the [[MTV Movie Award for Best Kiss]] (shared with his co-stars [[Jennifer Aniston]] and [[Emma Roberts]]) for his performance in ''[[We're the Millers]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2014/04/13/will-poulter-emma-roberts-jennifer-aniston-win-mtv-movie-award-best-kiss-2014/|title=Will Poulter, Emma Roberts & Jennifer Aniston Win MTV Best Kiss|date=13 April 2014|work=Hollywood life|accessdate=24 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Poulter was chosen as one of 23 upcoming actors to feature in July's issue of [[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]], with all actors being named \"Hollywood's Next Wave\". Other actors featured included [[Dylan O'Brien]] (Poulter's co-star in ''The Maze Runner'' series) and [[Jack Reynor]] (Poulter's co-star in ''Glassland'', ''Detroit'', and ''Midsommar'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/vf-hollywood/up-and-coming-actors-jaden-willow-smith|title=Hollywood's Next Wave|last=Smith|first=Krista|date=11 June 2014|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|accessdate=24 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nPoulter played [[Jim Bridger]] in the revenge-thriller ''[[The Revenant (2015 film)|The Revenant]]'', directed by [[Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu]], and starring [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] and [[Tom Hardy]]. The film centers on an 1820s frontiersman on a path of vengeance against those who left him for dead after a bear mauling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/2014/film/news/will-poulter-revenant-leonardo-dicaprio-1201190212|title=We\u2019re the Millers\" Will Poulter Joins Leonardo DiCaprio in \u2018The Revenant\u2019 (Exclusive)|last=Kroll|first=Justin|date=25 June 2014|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref> In 2017, he played the racist police officer Philip Krauss in the film ''[[Detroit (film)|Detroit]]'', about the [[1967 Detroit riots]]. His work in the film was praised with one critic calling him \"terrifyingly confident\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metro.us/entertainment/movies/detroit-review-kathryn-bigelow-john-boyega|title='Detroit' is a nightmarish history lesson about trauma|last=Prigge|first=Matt|date=23 July 2017|website=Metro|access-date=4 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nPoulter was initially cast as Pennywise the Clown in the [[It (2017 film)|2017 remake]] of the [[Stephen King]] miniseries ''[[It (1990 film)|It]]''. However, it was announced in June 2016 that [[Bill Skarsg\u00e5rd]] had been cast instead because Poulter dropped out due both to scheduling conflicts (the film was set to shoot at the same time as Poulter was set to begin work on ''Detroit'') as well as the departure of its initial director, Cary Fukunaga.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/stephen-kings-adaptation-finds-pennywise-898993 |title=Stephen King's 'It' Adaptation Finds Its Pennywise the Clown (Exclusive) |publisher=Hollywood Reporter |date=2 June 2016 |accessdate=22 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Poulter reprised his role as Gally in ''[[Maze Runner: The Death Cure]]'', the third and final installment of the ''Maze Runner'' film series. Later that year, he starred in the film ''[[The Little Stranger (film)|The Little Stranger]]'' as Roderick \"Roddy\" Ayres, a facially disfigured, haunted war veteran, and as game developer Colin Ritman in ''[[Black Mirror: Bandersnatch]]'', a standalone [[Interactive movie|interactive film]] of the ''Black Mirror'' television series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2018-12-31/bandersnatch-cast-black-mirror/|title=Meet the cast of Black Mirror's interactive film Bandersnatch|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=31 December 2018}}</ref> In 2019, he played the character of Mark in [[Ari Aster]]\u2019s horror film ''[[Midsommar (film)|Midsommar]]''.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Son of Rambow]]''\n| Lee Carter\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[The Chronicles of Narnia: The Voyage of the Dawn Treader]]''\n| [[Eustace Scrubb]]\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Wild Bill (2011 film)|Wild Bill]]''\n| Dean\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[We're the Millers]]''\n| Kenny Rossmore / Kenny Miller\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | 2014\n| ''[[Plastic (2014 film)|Plastic]]''\n| Fordy\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Maze Runner (film)|The Maze Runner]]''\n| Gally\n|\n|-\n|''A Plea For Grimsby''\n|Jone\n|\n|-\n|''[[Glassland]]''\n| Shane\n| \n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[The Revenant (2015 film)|The Revenant]]''\n| [[Jim Bridger]]\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Kids in Love (film)|Kids in Love]]''\n| Jack\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2017\n| ''[[War Machine (film)|War Machine]]''\n| Sgt. Rick Ortega\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Detroit (film)|Detroit]]''\n| Philip Krauss\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2| 2018\n| ''[[Maze Runner: The Death Cure]]''\n| Gally\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Little Stranger (film)|The Little Stranger]]''\n| Roderick \"Roddy\" Ayres\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2019\n|''Bainne''\n|Irish farmer\n|\n|-\n|''[[Midsommar (film)|Midsommar]]''\n| Mark\n|\n|}\n\n===Series===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|2007\n|''Comedy: Shuffle''\n|Find Your Folks Presenter \n|2 episodes\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Comedy Lab]]''\n|Various\n|Episode: \"Kids School of Comedy\"\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Lead Balloon]]''\n|Sweet Throwing Boy\n|Episode: \"Nuts\"\n|-\n|2009\u20132010\n|''[[School of Comedy]]''\n|various characters\n|8 episodes; also writer\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[The Fades (TV series)|The Fades]]''\n|Mac\n|Episode: \"Pilot\"\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Black Mirror]]''\n|Colin Ritman\n|Episode: \"[[Black Mirror: Bandersnatch|Bandersnatch]]\"\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''The Dark Pictures Anthology: Little Hope''\n| Andrew\n| Motion capture\n|}<br />\n==Awards and nominations==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=August 2019}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Year\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Work\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Award\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Category\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE\"|Result\n|-\n|2008\n|rowspan=\"2\"|''[[Son of Rambow]]''\n|[[British Independent Film Awards 2008|British Independent Film Awards]]\n|[[British Independent Film Awards 2008#Most Promising Newcomer|Most Promising Newcomer]]\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|2009\n|[[30th Young Artist Awards|Young Artist Awards]]\n|[[30th Young Artist Awards#Best Performance in an International Feature Film|Best Performance in an International Feature Film \u2013 Leading Young Performers]] <small>(shared with [[Bill Milner]])</small>\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|2010\n|rowspan=4|''[[The Chronicles of Narnia: The Voyage of the Dawn Treader]]''\n|Phoenix Film Critics Society\n|Best Performance by a Youth in a Leading or Supporting Role \u2013 Male\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2011\n|[[32nd Young Artist Awards|Young Artist Awards]]\n|Best Performance in a Feature Film \u2013 Young Ensemble Cast <small>(shared with [[Georgie Henley]] and [[Skandar Keynes]])</small>\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|[[Academy of Science Fiction, Fantasy and Horror Films]]\n|Best Performance by a Younger Actor\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|[[London Film Critics' Circle]]\n|Young British Performer of the Year\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Wild Bill (2011 film)|Wild Bill]]''\n|London Film Critics' Circle\n|Young British Performer of the Year\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|rowspan=6|2014\n|rowspan=6|''[[We're the Millers]]''\n|[[2014 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards]]\n|Choice Movie Liplock <small>(shared with [[Emma Roberts]] and [[Jennifer Aniston]])</small>\n|{{nominated}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[2014 MTV Movie Awards|MTV Movie Awards]]\n|[[2014 MTV Movie Awards#Breakthrough Performance|Breakthrough Perform